You measure the energy of a particle in an infinite square well, then immediately measure its position, and then immediately measure its energy again. What are the possible outcomes of the second energy measurement?

#pagebreak()
#set page(width: a_width, margin: a_margin)
#set text(size: a_size)
Any energy eigenvalue $E_n$ ($n=1, 2, 3, dots$) is possible.

#pagebreak()
#set page(width: a_width, margin: a_margin)
#set text(size: a_size)
Only the energy value obtained in the first measurement is possible.

#pagebreak()
#set page(width: a_width, margin: a_margin)
#set text(size: a_size)
Only $E_1, E_2, or E_3$ are possible.

#pagebreak()
#set page(width: a_width, margin: a_margin)
#set text(size: a_size)
The particle will always collapse to the ground state $E_1$.

#pagebreak()
#set page(width: i_width, height: auto, margin: i_margin)
#set text(size: i_size)
*Prerequisites for Sequential Quantum Measurements:*

- Wave function collapse: measurement collapses the state into an eigenstate of the measured observable.
- Position eigenstates: a position delta function $delta(x - x_0)$ contains a superposition of all energy eigenstates.
